docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Thousands of Islamic State foreign fighters and family members have escaped the American-led military campaign in eastern Syria, according to new classified American and other Western military and intelligence assessments, a flow that threatens to tarnish American declarations that the militant group has been largely defeated.

docs.abstract: As a businessman, Donald J. Trump never felt respected by the elites who shunned him. Now as president, he commands attention, if not admiration.
docs.snippet: As a businessman, Donald J. Trump never felt respected by the elites who shunned him. Now as president, he commands attention, if not admiration.
docs.lead_paragraph: DAVOS, Switzerland — By any measure, he made a lot of money, the kid from Queens, maybe not as much as he boasted, but a fortune. And yet never accepted, never respected, he remained on the outside pressing his nose against the window of the club of elites he both revered and resented.

headline.main: In Davos, a Club Trump Has Revered and Resented Finally Opens Its Doors
headline.print_headline: In Davos, a Club Revered And Resented by Trump Finally Opens Its Doors

docs.abstract: The charges against 13 Russians have injected a new twist into a debate that has consumed the political universe since the final hours of election night: How did Trump do it?
docs.snippet: The charges against 13 Russians have injected a new twist into a debate that has consumed the political universe since the final hours of election night: How did Trump do it?
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The detailed indictment of 13 Russians for intervening in the 2016 presidential election has rekindled a debate that had never fully gone away and now seems destined to become one of the great unresolved questions in American political history: Did Moscow tilt the election to Donald J. Trump?

headline.main: Indictment Leaves No Doubt: Russia Backed Trump. But Was It the Difference?
headline.print_headline: Moscow’s Hand Swirled in U.S., but Whether It Tipped Election Is Unclear

docs.abstract: Among the factors justices have considered in deciding when to step down are party loyalty, judicial legacy and the next presidential election.
docs.snippet: Among the factors justices have considered in deciding when to step down are party loyalty, judicial legacy and the next presidential election.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Supreme Court justices say they do not act politically when they decide cases. But they freely admit to taking account of politics in deciding when to retire. Most justices, for instance, try to step down under politically like-minded presidents.

headline.main: Will Anthony Kennedy Retire? What Influences a Justice’s Decision
headline.print_headline: Justices Consider Legacy and Loyalty In Departure Plans

docs.abstract: The indictment does not allege collusion but reveals in painstaking detail how Russians posed as American activists to boost Mr. Trump’s campaign.
docs.snippet: The indictment does not allege collusion but reveals in painstaking detail how Russians posed as American activists to boost Mr. Trump’s campaign.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Justice Department charged 13 Russians and three companies on Friday in a sprawling indictment that unveiled a sophisticated network designed to subvert the 2016 election and to support the Trump campaign. It stretched from an office in St. Petersburg, Russia, into the social feeds of Americans and ultimately reached the streets of election battleground states.

headline.main: 13 Russians Indicted as Mueller Reveals Effort to Aid Trump Campaign
headline.print_headline: Indictment Bares Russian Network To Twist 2016 Vote

docs.abstract: A year after planning a broad reorganization of the federal government, President Trump has signed a budget that expands every facet of the Washington swamp.
docs.snippet: A year after planning a broad reorganization of the federal government, President Trump has signed a budget that expands every facet of the Washington swamp.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When the Trump administration rolled out its 2018 budget last year, its “New Foundation for American Greatness” was billed as a road map for President Trump’s deconstruction of the administrative state. Domestic programs prized by Democrats would be cut, the diplomatic corps would be decimated, spending on the military would balloon and a wall would be funded on the southern border.

headline.main: With New Budget Deal, Trump Surrenders to the Administrative State
headline.print_headline: In Signing New Budget Deal, President Surrenders to Big Spending

byline.original: By Alan Rappeport and Mark Landler

docs.abstract: A resignation by the chief of staff, John F. Kelly, was not considered imminent, but his suggestion reflects the turmoil engulfing President Trump’s staff.
docs.snippet: A resignation by the chief of staff, John F. Kelly, was not considered imminent, but his suggestion reflects the turmoil engulfing President Trump’s staff.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — John F. Kelly, the White House chief of staff, told officials in the West Wing on Friday that he was willing to step down over his handling of allegations of spousal abuse against Rob Porter, the staff secretary who resigned in disgrace this week over the accusations, according to two officials aware of the discussions.

headline.main: Kelly Says He’s Willing to Resign as Abuse Scandal Roils White House
headline.print_headline: Under Fire, Kelly Is Said to Muse About Resigning

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — From the moment in March when President Trump proposed his budget for 2018, Washington has been struggling to reach any consensus on spending. Congress finally appears to have found one, largely without Mr. Trump’s help. Here’s a look at how lawmakers got there.
